{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aad996f6-f628-49bf-9f2c-594c4ae6e0f5","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps. Alternatively, use **PerfView** for deeper Windows ETW-based analysis.\n\n### Quick approach: `dotnet-trace`\n\n```powershell\n# Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### For deeper analysis: PerfView\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\nPerfView captures OS-level ETW events and gives flame graphs, thread-time views, and can show both managed and native stacks.\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for speed. Escalate to PerfView if you need to see native code, kernel time, or cross-process interactions.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1e544ea9-7615-4197-bf47-1c4e93440547","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a general knowledge question about performance diagnostics — no code changes or file operations needed. I'll give a concise, actionable answer.","outputTokens":339,"requestId":"502B:27A93C:1EFA82:26D4C9:69F5514F"},"id":"6fb869ed-1938-4fc6-98d2-d81902e75ca8","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:20:25.034Z","parentId":"8e0a727b-7cf5-478f-83ea-572263388a47"}
